              "videoId": "Ax1U04c4gaw",
              "textDisplay": "@rubyray777  If birth control worked for you than you don't have a severe case of PCOS. Severe PCOS is not controllable by birth control pills and it actually can make it worse and cause allot of extra symptoms. I started birth control pills at 11 after they found out I had PCOS and it was one of the worst mistakes I made in my life and if I could go back and change that decision I would. I got ovarian cysts very often because of birth control pills and since I've stopped taking them I have had a drastic decrease in symptoms, my period is back (not every month but on birth control I never had my periods, I never had ovulation and I still don't but at least something is happening), I lost 20 pounds suddenly after I quit and I didn't change my eating or exercise habits because I already was on a personal lifestyle plan from my dietician, my skin cleared up, my  anxiety and panic attacks got allot better, my body hair growth decreased and I even stopped sweating which I didn't even knew that it was a symptom until it went away when I quit. Birth control helps sometimes but if you have a severe case of PCOS it often does absolutely nothing but make things worse. Birth control pills fucked up my ovaries from all the cyst so they had to remove them because the pain was so bad every time that I wanted to die and couldn't move. I am a RN so not moving every time I was in pain wasn't an option so an ovariectomy was the only option. I was 21 when I had them removed and I always wanted to be a mother and experience being pregnant so that was really hard to accept especially at that age. You can't say that because it worked for you it will work for everyone. That's just such a naive thing to say. I followed a strict low carb lifestyle because of my weight and high blood sugars for 2 years under strict supervision from my doctor's and dietician and I lost 30 pounds and then I didn't lose anything anymore. I kept doing it for a year in hopes that it was a temporary halt but in the next year I lost 5 pounds in total and my dietician told me that it wasn't my fault, I did everything I was supposed to do, I ate what I was supposed to ate and I was very strict on myself, I didn't even go out for dinner for those 2 years so that I wouldn't be tempted to have a cheat meal because it really had become my lifestyle and I was afraid that if I slipped up once I would slowly start to lose motivation and control. I had a personal trainer that was part of the personal lifestyle program that also had my dietician, diabetic specialist and physical therapist, they worked together and it was one of the top 3 best programs for weight loss and lifestyle changes in my country. After 2 years with them she referred me to the hospital for a gastric bypass. I did everything I was supposed to do and fought with my weight, food and my self-esteem/insecurities for 20 years and then that all changed after my surgery and now I'm healthy and happy and my only regret is that I didn't do it sooner. I spent so much time, money and tears on my weight loss journey I feel sick just thinking about it. I know that surgery should be a last resort always but for me it was and if I waited longer I probably would have had permanent health issues. But allot of people can do it with the right recourses and assistance and I you should be proud of losing weight no matter how you did it but what works for one person does not work for everyone and I'm so sick of people trying to force their methods on others like they know best and they know everything about losing weight and the right way to do it but you don't. You know what works best for you and that's great but not every body or situation is the same and you really have no right to tell anyone how they should lose weight or that their way is wrong.               "videoId": "9DO49wzxeyU",
              "textDisplay": "@Harley B.  Bird Whisperer:  Sorry for the delayed reply. YT didn't notify me when you updated your previous comment.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI think it's helpful to differentiate between \u003cb\u003ewhat matters\u003c/b\u003e and *what is true*.  Far more things are true than actually matter.  So, I think it's best to agree on what matters before discussing what is true.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMost online policy discussions quickly devolve into bickering over facts (what is true) between people who don't agree on what matters... and it can enable people to move the goal posts when they come across inconvenient facts.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThat's why I'm not really interested in discussing the details of muzzle velocity and magazine capacities before defining the problem, and I try to avoid defining a problem according to a proposed solution--e.g., defining the problem as excessive muzzle velocities and magazine capacities.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI'm more in favor of starting with our values and concerns, and working backward to identify the various causes and influences.  Then, we can look for the best points of leverage to do the most good.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMy guess is that you want to reduce the total number of preventable civilian deaths and serious injuries (or maybe more generally to reduce suffering).  If that's the case, then we might look at the causes of preventable civilian deaths and serious injuries to see how gun-related causes rank.  For example, it might be the case that gun-related deaths are relatively low compared to other causesbut that we pay a lot of attention to the gun-related casualties because they grab headlines.
